The paper deals with the problem of designing distribution rules for sharing welfare among strategic agents, which is a central topic in game theory. The paper provides an exact characterization of the space of distribution rules that guarantee the existence of a Nash equilibrium in a specific class of games, which includes a variety of applications such as facility location, routing, network formation, and coverage games. This suggests that the paper is likely to be classified under cs.GT (Game Theory), which is the most relevant sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves computational tractability and optimization, which are common themes in sub-categories such as cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also deals with network formation and coverage games, which are relevant to sub-category cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
